## What happened

In .NET 11, **DSA support was removed from macOS**. Calling `DSA.Create()` (or any DSA signing/verification API) now throws at runtime on macOS. Windows and Linux are unaffected.

## How to fix it

Since you're **verifying legacy DSA signatures**, you can't simply switch the algorithm for existing signatures. Your options:

1. **Platform guard** — skip DSA verification on macOS or run it only on Linux/Windows:
   ```csharp
   if (!OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
   {
       using var dsa = DSA.Create();
       // verify signature...
   }
   ```

2. **Use a cross-platform crypto library** (e.g., [BouncyCastle](https://www.nuget.org/packages/BouncyCastle.Cryptography)) that provides its own DSA implementation independent of the OS:
   ```csharp
   // BouncyCastle example for DSA verification
   var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA256withDSA");
   verifier.Init(false, publicKey);
   verifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
   bool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
   ```

3. **Long-term: migrate signatures to ECDSA or Ed25519** — re-sign artifacts with a modern algorithm so DSA is no longer needed.

For a library that must verify existing DSA signatures on all three platforms, **option 2 (BouncyCastle)** is the most practical fix.
